To find out how many test tubes were needed for each of the other two experiments, we need to subtract the number of test tubes needed for the first experiment (2) from the total number of test tubes needed for all three experiments (8).

So, 8 - 2 = 6.

Since there are two identical experiments left, each will require half of these remaining test tubes. 

Therefore, Sara needed 3 test tubes for each of the other two experiments.
